  "prompt": "How much of myoglobin is there in pork and how much of Iron is there in the myoglobin in weight?",
  "response": "Myoglobin is a protein found in muscle tissue, and it contains iron. In general, myoglobin levels can vary by the type of meat and the specific cut. In pork, myoglobin content is typically lower than in red meats like beef and lamb, but it can still provide a good source of iron.\n\nPork muscle tissue generally contains about 0.1 to 0.25 grams of myoglobin per 100 grams of meat, though this can vary depending on the cut and whether the muscle is more used (like shoulder) or less used (like tenderloin). \n\nMyoglobin contains approximately 0.4% iron by weight. Therefore, if we take an average myoglobin content of about 0.2 grams per 100 grams of pork, that would yield:\n\n- Iron content in myoglobin:\n  \\[\n  0.2 \\text{ grams of myoglobin} \\times 0.004 \\text{ (iron percentage)} = 0.0008 \\text{ grams of iron}\n  \\]\n  or 0.8 milligrams.\n\nSo, in 100 grams of pork, you might find roughly 0.8 mg of iron coming from myoglobin. Keep in mind that this is a rough estimate, and actual values can vary based on the specific cut of meat and the diet of the animal. For more precise nutritional information, it would be best to consult specific nutritional databases or studies on pork.",
